In linguistics, a '''tenseless language''' is a language that does not have a [[Grammatical tense|grammatical category of tense]]. Tenseless languages can and do refer to [[time]] but they do so using lexical items such as adverbs or verbs, or by using combinations of [[grammatical aspect|aspect]], and [[mood (linguistics)|mood]], and words that establish time reference. Examples of tenseless languages are [[Burmese language|Burmese]], [[Dyirbal language|Dyirbal]],{{sfn|Comrie|1985|pp=50–53}} [[Chinese language|Chinese]], [[Malay language|Malay]] (including [[Indonesian language|Indonesian]]), and in some analyses [[Greenlandic language|Greenlandic]]{{sfn|Bittner|2005}} and [[Guaraní language|Guaraní]].{{sfn|Tonhauser|2011}}

